{"ts":"2026-06-27T22:19:09.081Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Reviewing Code Structure**\n\nI'm currently marveling at the elegant design. The presence of distinct helper repositories—`users_repo`, `clients_repo`, and `portal_items_repo`—within the backend, such as in `backend/app/repositories/users.py`, seems particularly well-structured. It makes the code so much clearer.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T22:19:11.040Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Investigating Seeding Strategy**\n\nI'm now diving deep into the seeding process. My focus has shifted to `backend/app/seed.py`. Initially, it seemed like the code was set up to manage a local SQLite database, but I'm now exploring extending this to seed our DynamoDB tables directly! The eureka moment is that if we use existing repositories, the DynamoDB tables will be seeded directly, whether mock or real! The table names in `settings` map to `GFF_USERS`, `GFF_CLIENTS`, and `GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`, confirmed via `.env`.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T22:19:12.460Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Analyzing Seed Data Requirements**\n\nI'm now clarifying the precise data needed for seeding, per the updated requirements. I'm focusing on the specific user roles: `gff_admin`, `client_admin`, and `client_member`. I need to ensure the correct client relationships and understand the nuances of the data. The documentation will cover the credentials. The goal is to set up a repeatable seed.\n\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T22:19:14.215Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Refining Client Data**\n\nI'm now revising the client data strategy. It's clear I must avoid \"fake real client names\" like actual company trademarks. I'm pivoting to more enterprise-neutral names for two clients, such as \"Sovereign Logistics Corp\" and \"Alpha Financial Services\". This also extends to logos, and I'll adapt the existing seeding data to match the new client names for the databases.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T22:19:16.554Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Clarifying User Seed Details**\n\nI'm now nailing down user details for seeding. I'm confirming the use of generic, neutral emails for users: `gff_admin@gff.ai`, `client_admin@gff.ai`, and `client_member@gff.ai`. I'm verifying the association of `client_id: \"1\"` for the client roles. For passwords, I'm leaning toward a simple, secure dev password.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T22:19:17.887Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Implementing DynamoDB Seeding**\n\nI'm now implementing the DynamoDB seeding process. I'll document the seed credentials in `docs/PHASE_6_AWS_FINAL_SETUP.md`. I've investigated `backend/app/seed.py` and `backend/app/repositories/dynamodb_client.py`. I'm going to create a Python script to seed the DynamoDB tables. I'll update `backend/app/seed.py` to seed the local SQLite database and AWS DynamoDB tables based on environment configuration. It is invoked as `backend:seed`.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
