{"ts":"2026-06-27T22:22:49.954Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Fixing The Type Error**\n\nI'm thrilled the CRUD tests are green! The focus now shifts to the `TypeError` in `backend/app/seed.py`. To resolve the float type issue, I plan to import `Decimal` and apply the `convert_floats` strategy. I think this will do the trick!\n\n\n**Implementing Decimal Conversion**\n\nI've crafted a `convert_floats_to_decimals` function to handle the `TypeError`. I can now elegantly address the root cause, and have a clear solution for the seed data conversion. I'm going to apply the helper in `seed_aws_dynamodb()` to convert all float values to Decimal objects before inserting items into DynamoDB. It's a clean implementation that completely prevents floats from interacting with DynamoDB.\n\n\n**Verifying Data Integrity**\n\nI'm now cross-referencing seed data with the test suite requirements. My current focus is to verify that the clients used in `test_backend_smoke.py` align precisely with the expected seeded clients. I'm confirming the exact client names and IDs required by the tests, paying close attention to avoiding trademarked names. It's a key part of ensuring full integration test coverage, and now I have a list of all 4 clients needed.\n\n\n**Analyzing Test Dependencies**\n\nI'm now digging into `test_backend_smoke.py` to understand the test's reliance on `\"Chevron Corporation\"`. It seems the test leverages `\"Chevron\"` specifically in comments and document titles, but doesn't explicitly assert the *existence* of a client with that exact name. This is encouraging! I need to confirm whether the test uses the client name `\"Chevron Corporation\"`. My next step is to replace the client name with `\"Sovereign Energy Corp\"`, update the test case title and comments accordingly, and then see if the test still passes when I keep the email. It looks like I have a path forward here.\n\n\n"}}
